    <li class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="li-comment-1597361">

      <div class="comment-wrap" id="comment-1597361">

        <div class="author-avatar">
          <img src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAP///wAAACH5BAAAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw==" width="50" height="50" class="lazyload-gravatar" alt="User Avatar" data-src="https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/92c22e51a4b758feec86dee8cd7c8a6f?s=160&d=retro&r=pg">
          <svg class="half-circle" width="80px" height="80px">
            <use xlink:href="#half-circle"></use>
          </svg>
        </div>

        <div class="comment-body">

          <div class="comment-author-wrap vcard">
            <div class="comment-time"><time datetime="2015-10-06T06:22:41+00:00">October 6, 2015</time></div> <div class="comment-author"><a href="Dan"><span class="screen-reader">Permalink to comment</span>#</a> Dan</div>
            
          </div>
          <div class="comment-content">

            <p>Try adding a background color to the <code>.navigation a</code> and you will see that they are not the same. Using <code>inline-block</code> keeps you dependent on the browser default use of extra space left and right of inline <code>li</code> elements. This rendering can be fixed by floating the <code>li</code> elements, but <code>flexbox</code> is a nicer (modern) way of achieving that effect.</p>

          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="comment-actions">
          <div class="reply">
                      </div>
        </div>

      </div>
      
    
